        <div class="text-xs font-bold uppercase tracking-widest text-red-brand mb-2">Compliance · April 2026 · 11 min read</div>
        <h1 class="text-4xl font-bold tracking-tight mb-4 leading-tight">Restaurant Fire Safety Requirements in Newark, NJ: What Every Operator Needs to Know</h1>
        <p class="text-lg text-gray-500 leading-relaxed mb-8">Newark's Ironbound district — one of the most dense concentrations of Portuguese, Spanish, and Brazilian restaurants on the East Coast — creates some of New Jersey's most active kitchen fire suppression compliance demand. The NJUFC applies unique requirements distinct from the IFC used in neighboring states. Here's what Newark restaurant operators need to know about kitchen fire safety compliance.</p>
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold tracking-tight mb-3">NFPA 96 Kitchen Suppression Requirements</h2>
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">All commercial cooking operations in Newark producing grease-laden vapors must install and maintain an automatic wet chemical fire suppression system under NFPA 96. This applies to restaurants, bars with food service, hotel kitchens, and corporate cafeterias. Newark's Ironbound district contains hundreds of restaurants and food service operations within a compact area — creating one of the highest densities of NFPA 96 compliance obligations per block in the state. New Jersey's NJUFC requires semi-annual kitchen suppression inspection by a contractor holding NJ Division of Fire Safety licensing — not just a standard fire protection license from another state.</p>
        <h3 class="text-lg font-bold mb-3">Semi-Annual Inspection Requirement</h3>
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">NFPA 96 requires kitchen suppression systems to be inspected and serviced semi-annually — twice per year — by a licensed contractor. Records must be maintained on-site and available for Newark Fire Department inspection. Semi-annual means every six months from the last inspection date, not twice per calendar year.</p>
        <h3 class="text-lg font-bold mb-3">Hood Cleaning Requirements</h3>
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">NFPA 96 requires hood cleaning at intervals based on cooking volume: quarterly for high-volume operations (solid fuel cooking, charbroiling, wok cooking, high-volume fryers), semi-annually for moderate volume, annually for low-volume like pizza ovens. Hood cleaning records must be maintained on-site.</p>
        <h3 class="text-lg font-bold mb-3">Class K Fire Extinguisher</h3>
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">A Class K extinguisher must be within 30 feet of all cooking surfaces producing grease-laden vapors. Class K units are specifically designed for cooking oil fires — standard ABC dry chemical is not an adequate substitute. Class K units require annual inspection alongside other extinguishers.</p>
