        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold tracking-tight mb-3 mt-8">Common Restaurant Fire Safety Violations in Newark</h2>
        <div class="flex flex-col gap-3 mb-8"><div class="flex items-start gap-3 p-3 bg-red-light rounded-lg border border-red-200"><span class="text-red-brand font-bold flex-shrink-0">!</span><span class="text-sm text-gray-700">Overdue semi-annual suppression in Ironbound restaurant kitchens — busy family-owned operations sometimes defer compliance</span></div><div class="flex items-start gap-3 p-3 bg-red-light rounded-lg border border-red-200"><span class="text-red-brand font-bold flex-shrink-0">!</span><span class="text-sm text-gray-700">Missing Class K extinguishers in Ironbound commercial kitchens with high-volume cooking surfaces</span></div><div class="flex items-start gap-3 p-3 bg-red-light rounded-lg border border-red-200"><span class="text-red-brand font-bold flex-shrink-0">!</span><span class="text-sm text-gray-700">Hood cleaning documentation missing — NJ requires records on-site for inspector review</span></div><div class="flex items-start gap-3 p-3 bg-red-light rounded-lg border border-red-200"><span class="text-red-brand font-bold flex-shrink-0">!</span><span class="text-sm text-gray-700">Using a contractor without NJ Division of Fire Safety licensing — invalidates inspection records</span></div></div>
        <div class="border border-gray-200 rounded-lg p-4 mb-4"><h3 class="text-sm font-bold mb-2">Newark's Ironbound has family-owned restaurants operating for decades. Do older restaurants still need to comply with current suppression requirements?</h3><p class="text-sm text-gray-600">Yes. NJUFC kitchen suppression requirements apply to all operating commercial cooking facilities regardless of how long they have been in operation. There is no grandfather exemption for established restaurants. If your Ironbound restaurant has a cooking hood and suppression system, it requires semi-annual inspection. If it has cooking operations without a suppression system, that is a current code violation. Newark Fire Department has increased Ironbound enforcement in recent years.</p></div>
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold tracking-tight mb-3 mt-8">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
        <div class="flex flex-col gap-4 mb-8"><div class="border border-gray-200 rounded-lg p-4"><h3 class="text-sm font-bold mb-2">Does every Newark restaurant need a kitchen fire suppression system?</h3><p class="text-sm text-gray-600">Yes. All commercial cooking operations in Newark producing grease-laden vapors must have an automatic wet chemical suppression system under NFPA 96 and the New Jersey Uniform Fire Code (NJUFC). This applies to restaurants, bars with food service, hotel kitchens, and corporate cafeterias.</p></div><div class="border border-gray-200 rounded-lg p-4"><h3 class="text-sm font-bold mb-2">How often does kitchen fire suppression need to be inspected in Newark?</h3><p class="text-sm text-gray-600">NFPA 96 requires semi-annual inspection — twice per year — for all commercial kitchen suppression systems. Inspection must be performed by a licensed contractor and documented. The Newark Fire Department enforces this requirement.</p></div><div class="border border-gray-200 rounded-lg p-4"><h3 class="text-sm font-bold mb-2">How much does kitchen suppression inspection cost in Newark?</h3><p class="text-sm text-gray-600">$200–$450 per system per system. Budget for two inspections annually.</p></div><div class="border border-gray-200 rounded-lg p-4"><h3 class="text-sm font-bold mb-2">What is the most common kitchen fire safety violation in Newark?</h3><p class="text-sm text-gray-600">Common violations in Newark include: Overdue semi-annual suppression in Ironbound restaurant kitchens — busy family-owned operations sometimes defer compliance; Missing Class K extinguishers in Ironbound commercial kitchens with high-volume cooking surfaces.</p></div><div class="border border-gray-200 rounded-lg p-4"><h3 class="text-sm font-bold mb-2">Who licenses kitchen suppression contractors in NJ?</h3><p class="text-sm text-gray-600">The NJ Division of Fire Safety ((609) 633-6132) licenses fire protection contractors statewide. Verify your suppression contractor holds current NJ credentials before scheduling service.</p></div></div>
